The paper deals with a problem in graph theory related to cliques and independent sets, which falls under the category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The problem involves finding a minimum number of cuts separating cliques from stable sets in a graph, which is a communication complexity problem and hence can also be categorized under computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also discusses results related to graph theory and combinatorics, which are subfields of theoretical computer science and can be categorized under cs.GT. The paper uses techniques such as Vapnik-Chervonenkis dimension and regularity lemma, which are related to discrete structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the equivalence of the problem with other well-known problems such as the Alon-Saks-Seymour Conjecture and the stubborn problem, which are related to computational complexity and graph theory, respectively, and hence can be categorized under cs.CG.
